The TodoList component also has a responsibility issue—it accepts a `todoListId` prop but then fetches its own data instead of receiving it from above.

The architecture maintains separate caches for the all-list and detail queries of the same data, which is why the cache helper functions in `todoListCache.ts` got so complex. For a take-home project, this feels overengineered.

The mutation handlers in `useTodoListItemMutations` are recreated on every render since they're plain functions closing over the mutation methods. Even though TodoListItem uses memo with callback identity checks, the memoization breaks when the parent rerenders and creates new handler references. The hook creates new function references on every render, so when `TodoList` calls `useTodoListItemMutations`, it gets fresh `handleUpdateItem` and `handleDeleteItem` functions each time. These get passed down to `TodoListItem`, where the custom memo comparison checks reference equality—which will always fail since they're new functions. This completely defeats the memoization and causes unnecessary re-renders. Meanwhile, `useTodoListHeader` is using `useMemo` to wrap the form submission handler, which is a better approach but still depends on its dependencies staying stable.

