## 3. Critical Issues

### 3.1 `React.memo` on `TodoListItem` is completely defeated

This is the single most damaging issue in the submission.

```168:181:src/features/todoLists/components/TodoList/TodoListItem/TodoListItem.tsx
function arePropsEqual(prev: TodoListItemProps, next: TodoListItemProps) {
  return (
    prev.todoListId === next.todoListId &&
    prev.isDraggable === next.isDraggable &&
    prev.item.id === next.item.id &&
    prev.item.name === next.item.name &&
    prev.item.description === next.item.description &&
    prev.item.done === next.item.done &&
    prev.onUpdateItem === next.onUpdateItem &&
    prev.onDeleteItem === next.onDeleteItem
  );
}

export const TodoListItem = memo(TodoListItemComponent, arePropsEqual);
```

The comparison checks `prev.onUpdateItem === next.onUpdateItem` and `prev.onDeleteItem === next.onDeleteItem`. But these callbacks come from `useTodoListItemMutations`, which returns **new function references every render**:

```57:66:src/features/todoLists/components/TodoList/TodoListItem/useTodoListItemMutations.ts
  return {
    handleUpdateItem: (todoItemId: number, updates: UpdateTodoItemDto) => {
      if (todoListId <= 0) return;
      updateItemMutation.mutate({ todoItemId, updates });
    },
    handleDeleteItem: (todoItemId: number) => {
      if (todoListId <= 0) return;
      deleteItemMutation.mutate(todoItemId);
    },
  };
```

These are plain function expressions -- not wrapped in `useCallback`. Every time `TodoList` re-renders (which happens on any state change -- filter, search, drag), **every `TodoListItem` re-renders** despite the memo. The custom comparison is dead code.

**Why this matters:** The candidate went through visible effort to create a custom equality function, which signals they believe they understand memoization. But they missed the most fundamental requirement: callback identity stability. An interviewer would see this as either cargo-culting or incomplete understanding of React's rendering model.

**Fix:** Wrap `handleUpdateItem` and `handleDeleteItem` in `useCallback` inside `useTodoListItemMutations`, or use mutation refs for stable identity.

### 3.2 `useTodoListHeaderMutations` has the same callback instability problem

```118:131:src/features/todoLists/components/TodoList/TodoListHeader/useTodoListHeaderMutations.ts
  return {
    handleUpdateName: (name: string) => {
      if (todoListId <= 0) return;
      updateNameMutation.mutate(name);
    },
    handleDeleteList: () => {
      if (todoListId <= 0) return;
      deleteListMutation.mutate();
    },
    handleAddItem: (name: string) => {
      if (todoListId <= 0) return;
      addItemMutation.mutate(name);
    },
  };
```

These are consumed by `useTodoListHeader` whose `useCallback` wrappers depend on `onUpdateName` and `onAddItem` -- which are the unstable references above. So the entire memoization chain in the header path is also broken: `useCallback` depends on an unstable dep, making it re-create every render anyway.

### 3.3 Query keys are not hierarchically structured

```1:4:src/shared/query/todoLists.ts
export const todoListQueryKeys = {
  all: ['todoLists'] as const,
  detail: (todoListId: number) => ['todoList', todoListId] as const,
};
```

`all` uses `'todoLists'` (plural) while `detail` uses `'todoList'` (singular). This means you cannot do `queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: ['todoLists'] })` and have it also invalidate detail queries. This is a well-known TanStack Query antipattern. The standard approach is:

```typescript
const todoListQueryKeys = {
  all: ['todoLists'] as const,
  detail: (id: number) => ['todoLists', id] as const,
};
```

With hierarchical keys, invalidating `['todoLists']` cascades to all detail queries. The current structure forces the mutation handlers to manually cancel and update both caches everywhere, which is exactly what leads to the verbose `todoListCache.ts` helpers.

